The United States has fifty states, each with its own unique name and history. Many of these state names have interesting origins, from Native American words to historical figures or places in Europe. Here are some examples: 
Alabama - named after the Alabama River which was named by the Creek Indians; 
Arizona – derived from the Spanish word “arizona” meaning “little spring”; 
California – derived from the name given to the region by the Spanish explorer Juan Cabrillo who sailed under the flag of Castile; 
Colorado – derived from the Spanish language, literally translating as ‘colored red’ due to the color of the earth found there; 
Florida – derived from the Spanish word for 'flowery' (‘florida') ; 
Georgia – named after King George II of Great Britain; 
Illinois – derived from the Algonquian Indian word "illiniwek" meaning "tribe of superior men"; 
Indiana – derived from the Delaware Indian word "ina-pah-hata," meaning "land of the settling waters;" 
Iowa – derived from the Ioway people, one of the many Siouan tribes native to the area; 
Kansas – derived from the Kansa tribe, one of the several Sioux tribes native to the area; 
Maryland – derived from the Latin phrase “Terra Mariae,” which means “Land of Mary.” The colony was founded as a Catholic haven; 
Michigan – derived from the Ojibwa word “mishigamaa”, meaning “large water”; 
Mississippi – derived from the Chippewa word “msiskiy” meaning “great river”; 
Montana – derived from the Spanish word “montaña” meaning mountainous terrain; 
Nebraska – derived from the Oto-Missouri dialect of the Sioux language, meaning “flat water”; 
New Hampshire – derived from the phrase “new Hampshire Grants,” referring to land grants made to veterans of the Revolutionary War; 
Ohio – derived from the Iroquois word “ohiyo” meaning “good fishing place”; 
Oklahoma – derived from two Choctaw words, okla and homma, meaning “red people”; 
Oregon – derived from the French term “Orégon,” meaning “shining or gleaming gold”; 
Pennsylvania – derived from the Pennsylvania Dutch word Penn’sylvania, meaning “Penn’s woods”; 
South Carolina – derived from the Carolinian language, meaning “the land of the free”; 
Texas – derived from the Caddo word “tejas” meaning “friends”; 
Utah – derived from the Ute language, meaning “people of the mountains”; 
Vermont – derived from the Abenaki word “bermontogue,” meaning “green mountains”.
